---
/**
 * Tutorial 05 -- LLM Streaming
 *
 * The client:llm directive streams tokens from a Large Language Model
 * endpoint into the DOM. It builds on the same SSE transport as
 * client:stream but adds LLM-specific features:
 *
 *   - Token-by-token append mode (streaming text as it arrives)
 *   - Morph mode (structured HTML updates from the model)
 *   - Tool call support (function calling with start/delta/end lifecycle)
 *   - ABR quality tiers (adapt rendering complexity to device capability)
 *
 * In this tutorial you will:
 *   1. Understand the client:llm directive and its data attributes
 *   2. Learn the LLM SSE message protocol (text, tool-call-*, done, error)
 *   3. See how ABR quality tiers gate rendering complexity
 *   4. Handle LLM lifecycle events
 *   5. Understand the relationship between LLM streaming and generative UI
 */

import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="LLM Streaming">

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 1: What is LLM Streaming?
       ============================================================

       LLM responses arrive as a stream of tokens, not a single
       response. Rather than waiting for the full response and then
       rendering it, czap streams tokens into the DOM as they arrive.

       This is "generative UI" -- the UI is being generated in real
       time by the model. czap treats this as an adaptive media
       stream, similar to how video adapts quality to bandwidth.

       The client:llm directive:
         1. Opens an EventSource to the LLM endpoint
         2. Parses incoming token chunks
         3. Appends text to the DOM (or morphs structured HTML)
         4. Respects the device's quality tier (ABR)
         5. Dispatches lifecycle events for each phase
  -->

  <h1>05 -- LLM Streaming</h1>

  <p>
    The <code>client:llm</code> directive streams tokens from an LLM
    endpoint into the DOM. It treats LLM output as adaptive media --
    adjusting rendering complexity based on the device's capability tier.
  </p>

  <div class="note">
    <strong>Key idea:</strong> czap's generative UI pipeline treats LLM
    streaming the same way video streaming treats bandwidth. A powerful
    device gets rich, interactive rendering. A constrained device gets
    clean text. The content is the same; the presentation adapts.
  </div>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 2: The Markup

       To enable LLM streaming on an element:

       data-czap-llm-url="/api/chat"
         The SSE endpoint that streams LLM tokens.

       client:llm
         The Astro client directive registered by @czap/astro.

       Optional attributes:

       data-czap-llm-mode="append" (default) or "morph"
         - "append": tokens are appended as text nodes (streaming text)
         - "morph": tokens are accumulated and set as innerHTML
                    (for structured HTML output from the model)

       data-czap-llm-target=".output"
         CSS selector for the child element to stream into. If
         omitted, tokens stream into the directive element itself.
  -->

  <h2>The Markup</h2>

  <pre><code>&lt;!-- Append mode: tokens stream in as text, character by character --&gt;
&lt;div
  data-czap-llm-url="/api/chat"
  data-czap-llm-mode="append"
  client:llm
&gt;
  &lt;p class="placeholder"&gt;Thinking...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- Morph mode: accumulated tokens become innerHTML (for HTML output) --&gt;
&lt;div
  data-czap-llm-url="/api/chat"
  data-czap-llm-mode="morph"
  data-czap-llm-target=".output"
  client:llm
&gt;
  &lt;div class="output"&gt;Generating...&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 3: The LLM SSE Protocol

       The server sends JSON messages over SSE, similar to
       client:stream but with LLM-specific message types:

       "text"
         A chunk of text from the model. The directive appends it
         (in append mode) or accumulates it (in morph mode).
         Example: { "type": "text", "content": "Hello, " }

       "tool-call-start"
         The model is starting a tool/function call.
         Example: { "type": "tool-call-start", "toolName": "search" }

       "tool-call-delta"
         Partial tool call arguments (streamed JSON).
         Example: { "type": "tool-call-delta", "toolArgs": "{\"query\":" }

       "tool-call-end"
         Tool call is complete. The directive fires czap:llm-tool-end
         with the parsed arguments.
         Example: { "type": "tool-call-end" }

       "done"
         The model finished generating. Connection closes.
         Example: { "type": "done" }

       "error"
         An error occurred. Connection closes.
         Example: { "type": "error", "content": "Rate limit exceeded" }

       The directive also handles plain text SSE messages (when the
       data field is not valid JSON, it's treated as a text chunk).
       This means it works with simple LLM proxies that just forward
       raw token text.
  -->

  <h2>The LLM Protocol</h2>

  <p>
    Your LLM endpoint sends JSON messages over SSE. The directive
    understands these message types:
  </p>

  <pre><code>// Server-side: stream LLM tokens (Node.js example)
res.writeHead(200, {'{'}&br;
  'Content-Type': 'text/event-stream',
  'Cache-Control': 'no-cache',
  'Connection': 'keep-alive',
{'}'});

// Stream text tokens as they arrive from the model
for await (const token of llmStream) {'{'}&br;
  res.write(`data: ${'{'}&br;JSON.stringify({'{'}&br;
    type: 'text',
    content: token
  {'}'}){'}'}\\n\\n`);
{'}'}

// Signal completion
res.write(`data: ${'{'}&br;JSON.stringify({'{'}&br;
  type: 'done'
{'}'}){'}'}\\n\\n`);
res.end();</code></pre>

  <h3>Tool Calls</h3>

  <p>
    When the model invokes a tool (function calling), the directive
    buffers the arguments and fires lifecycle events:
  </p>

  <pre><code>// Server sends tool call lifecycle messages:
data: {'{'}"type":"tool-call-start","toolName":"searchDocs"{'}'}

// Arguments stream in chunks (partial JSON):
data: {'{'}"type":"tool-call-delta","toolArgs":"{\"query\": \"czap bound"{'}'}
data: {'{'}"type":"tool-call-delta","toolArgs":"aries\"}"{'}'}

// Tool call complete -- directive parses accumulated JSON
// and fires czap:llm-tool-end with { name, args }:
data: {'{'}"type":"tool-call-end"{'}'}</code></pre>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 4: ABR Quality Tiers

       ABR = Adaptive Bitrate Rendering. The czap detect script
       evaluates the device's capabilities and assigns a tier:

         "static"      -- Very constrained device. No LLM content rendered.
         "styled"      -- Plain text, minimal styling.
         "reactive"    -- Styled text with transitions. Default for most devices.
         "interactive" -- Full interactivity, animations, rich rendering.

       The client:llm directive reads data-czap-tier from <html>
       and gates rendering accordingly:

         - In "static" tier: text from the LLM is NOT rendered at
           all (the element stays in its skeleton/placeholder state).
           This prevents overwhelming very constrained devices.

         - In all other tiers: text is streamed normally.

       Your CSS can further adapt based on the tier to control how
       richly the streamed content is presented.
  -->

  <h2>ABR Quality Tiers</h2>

  <p>
    The directive reads <code>data-czap-tier</code> from <code>&lt;html&gt;</code>
    (set by the detect script) to adapt rendering complexity:
  </p>

  <div class="tier-grid">
    <div class="tier-card">
      <h3>static</h3>
      <p>
        LLM content is <strong>not rendered</strong>. The placeholder
        stays visible. This protects very constrained devices (low
        memory, few cores) from being overwhelmed by streaming DOM updates.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="tier-card">
      <h3>styled</h3>
      <p>
        Plain text output, minimal styling. No animations or transitions.
        Content streams in but the presentation is deliberately simple.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="tier-card">
      <h3>reactive</h3>
      <p>
        Styled output with CSS transitions. The default tier for most
        devices. Smooth token-by-token appearance.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="tier-card">
      <h3>interactive</h3>
      <p>
        Full rendering: animations, interactive elements, rich formatting.
        For powerful devices with plenty of headroom.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <pre><code>/* Tier-aware CSS for LLM output containers: */
[data-czap-tier="static"] .llm-output {'{'}&br;
  /* Don't show streaming content on static-tier devices */
  display: none;
{'}'}

[data-czap-tier="styled"] .llm-output {'{'}&br;
  /* Simple text, no animations */
  animation: none;
{'}'}

[data-czap-tier="reactive"] .llm-output {'{'}&br;
  /* Smooth fade-in for each token batch */
  animation: czap-fade 0.15s ease-out;
{'}'}

[data-czap-tier="interactive"] .llm-output {'{'}&br;
  /* Rich rendering with typing cursor animation */
  animation: czap-type 0.05s steps(1);
{'}'}</code></pre>

  <div class="note">
    <strong>Adaptive Bitrate Rendering:</strong> Just as video streaming
    adjusts quality to bandwidth, czap adjusts UI complexity to device
    capability. The LLM generates the same content; the rendering pipeline
    adapts the presentation. A flagship phone gets typing animations. A
    budget device gets clean text. Both get the information.
  </div>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 5: Live Demo

       This demo element has client:llm pointed at /api/chat.
       Since there's no actual LLM server running in this tutorial,
       it shows placeholder content. The lifecycle event listener
       below updates the status text when events fire.
  -->

  <h2>Live Demo</h2>

  <p>
    The element below is wired to <code>/api/chat</code>. In a real app,
    LLM tokens would stream in character by character. Here it shows
    fallback content since no LLM endpoint is running.
  </p>

  <!-- --------------------------------------------------------
       The LLM streaming container.

       data-czap-llm-url: points to the LLM SSE endpoint.
       data-czap-llm-mode: "append" streams text as text nodes;
                           "morph" accumulates into innerHTML.
       data-czap-llm-target: optional CSS selector for the
                             child element to receive tokens.

       When the directive hydrates, it:
         1. Opens new EventSource("/api/chat")
         2. Checks data-czap-tier (skips rendering in "static" tier)
         3. On "text" chunks: appends text nodes (append mode)
         4. On "tool-call-*": buffers args, dispatches events
         5. On "done": fires czap:llm-done, closes connection
  -------------------------------------------------------- -->
  <div
    class="llm-target"
    id="llm-demo"
    data-czap-llm-url="/api/chat"
    data-czap-llm-mode="append"
  >
    <p class="llm-status">Waiting for LLM stream...</p>
    <div class="llm-output">
      <!-- In append mode, tokens appear here as text nodes -->
      <span class="placeholder-text">
        Connect a real LLM endpoint at <code>/api/chat</code> to see
        tokens stream in here.
      </span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 6: Lifecycle Events

       The directive dispatches custom events at each phase of the
       LLM streaming lifecycle:

       czap:llm-start       -- EventSource opened successfully
       czap:llm-token       -- each text chunk arrived
                               detail: { text, accumulated }
       czap:llm-tool-start  -- model began a tool/function call
                               detail: { name }
       czap:llm-tool-end    -- tool call complete, args parsed
                               detail: { name, args }
       czap:llm-done        -- generation finished
                               detail: { accumulated }
       czap:llm-error       -- error or connection failure
                               detail: { message | reason }

       These events let you build UI around the streaming process:
       show a spinner on start, update a token counter on each token,
       render tool call results, show a "copy" button on done.
  -->

  <h2>Lifecycle Events</h2>

  <pre><code>const el = document.querySelector('[data-czap-llm-url]');

el.addEventListener('czap:llm-start', () =&gt; {'{'}&br;
  console.log('LLM generation started');
{'}'});

el.addEventListener('czap:llm-token', (e) =&gt; {'{'}&br;
  // e.detail.text -- the new token(s) in this chunk
  // e.detail.accumulated -- all tokens received so far
  console.log('Token:', e.detail.text);
{'}'});

el.addEventListener('czap:llm-tool-start', (e) =&gt; {'{'}&br;
  console.log('Tool call started:', e.detail.name);
{'}'});

el.addEventListener('czap:llm-tool-end', (e) =&gt; {'{'}&br;
  // e.detail.args is the parsed JSON from accumulated deltas
  console.log('Tool result:', e.detail.name, e.detail.args);
{'}'});

el.addEventListener('czap:llm-done', (e) =&gt; {'{'}&br;
  console.log('Complete. Full text:', e.detail.accumulated);
{'}'});

el.addEventListener('czap:llm-error', (e) =&gt; {'{'}&br;
  console.log('Error:', e.detail.message ?? e.detail.reason);
{'}'});</code></pre>

  <!-- ============================================================
       Demo script: listens for lifecycle events and updates
       the status text in the demo element above.
  -->

  <script>
    const demo = document.getElementById('llm-demo');
    const status = demo?.querySelector('.llm-status');

    demo?.addEventListener('czap:llm-start', () => {
      if (status) status.textContent = 'LLM connected -- streaming tokens...';
    });

    demo?.addEventListener('czap:llm-done', () => {
      if (status) status.textContent = 'Generation complete.';
    });

    demo?.addEventListener('czap:llm-error', () => {
      if (status) status.textContent = 'LLM unavailable (no endpoint running for this demo).';
    });
  </script>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 7: Generative UI Pipeline

       The LLM directive is part of czap's broader "generative UI"
       pipeline. The full picture:

       1. LLM generates tokens (text or structured output)
       2. client:llm streams them into the DOM
       3. ABR quality tiers gate rendering complexity
       4. Boundaries adapt layout based on device state
       5. Themes style everything coherently
       6. The compositor manages animation budgets

       Each piece is independent but they compose naturally:
         - An LLM response renders inside a boundary-aware container
         - The ABR tier affects how rich the LLM output looks
         - Theme tokens style the LLM output
         - The compositor ensures streaming doesn't blow the frame budget
  -->

  <h2>The Bigger Picture: Generative UI</h2>

  <p>
    The LLM directive is one piece of czap's generative UI pipeline:
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>LLM generates tokens</strong> -- text or structured output from the model</li>
    <li><strong>client:llm streams them</strong> -- tokens appear in the DOM as they arrive</li>
    <li><strong>ABR tiers gate rendering</strong> -- complexity adapts to device capability</li>
    <li><strong>Boundaries adapt layout</strong> -- viewport/device signals control structure</li>
    <li><strong>Themes style coherently</strong> -- light/dark, brand variants apply consistently</li>
    <li><strong>The compositor manages budgets</strong> -- animation frames stay within budget</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    Together, these systems treat LLM output as adaptive media: the same
    content, rendered at the quality level the device can sustain smoothly.
  </p>

  <h2>What You Learned</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><code>client:llm</code> streams LLM tokens into a DOM element via SSE.</li>
    <li><code>data-czap-llm-url</code> points to the LLM streaming endpoint.</li>
    <li>Append mode streams text as text nodes; morph mode accumulates HTML.</li>
    <li>Tool calls have a start/delta/end lifecycle with buffered argument parsing.</li>
    <li>ABR quality tiers adapt rendering -- <code>static</code> tier suppresses rendering entirely.</li>
    <li>Lifecycle events (<code>czap:llm-*</code>) let you build UI around the streaming process.</li>
    <li>The LLM directive composes with boundaries, themes, and the compositor.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="note">
    <strong>Congratulations!</strong> You have completed the czap tutorial.
    You now understand the five core concepts: boundaries, tokens, themes,
    server streaming, and LLM streaming. Each is independent, but they
    compose into a coherent adaptive rendering pipeline.
  </div>

</Base>

<style>
  .llm-target {
    padding: 1.5rem;
    border: 2px dashed #4f46e5;
    border-radius: 8px;
    margin: 1rem 0 2rem;
    min-height: 120px;
    background: #fafafe;
  }

  .llm-status {
    color: #4f46e5;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  .llm-output {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  .placeholder-text {
    color: #6b7280;
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .tier-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr));
    gap: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }

  .tier-card {
    background: #fff;
    border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;
    border-radius: 8px;
    padding: 1.25rem;
  }

  .tier-card h3 {
    color: #4f46e5;
    font-family: 'SF Mono', 'Fira Code', monospace;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .tier-card p {
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }
</style>
